name: Curtis Northcutt
title: CEO & Co-Founder @ Cleanlab. MIT PhD in CS. Making AI work reliably for people. Former Google, Oculus, Amazon, FAIR, Microsoft
about:
I am fortunate to work with a world-class team that inspires me every day. We're on a mission to empower people with GenAI that actually works. We sell AI-powered infra that enables businesses to build end-to-end agents and GenAI systems 10x faster. We transform messy enterprise data into a high-quality AI knowledge base — handling everything from ETL and chunking to de-duplication and curation. Used by 100+ of the Fortune-500. Raised $30M from Bain, Databricks, Menlo, & TQ. Get end-to-end reliable AI today: sales@cleanlab.ai.

My contributions focus on:
• AI that works with messy, real-world, human data
• AI to empower human intelligence, empathy, and capabilities

Bio (see curtisnorthcutt.com):
I completed my Ph.D. in Computer Science at MIT,  advised by quantum computer inventor (and friend) Isaac Chuang. Before that, I was awarded the NSF Fellowship and MIT Morris Joseph Levin Masters Thesis Award for my work at MIT. I also TA'd graduate machine learning (6.867) at MIT. Before that, I graduated as valedictorian from Vanderbilt University (2009-2013) where I majored in math and CS and was awarded the Barry M. Goldwater National Scholarship.

My work spans the theory and applications of AI including uncertainty quantification and augmenting human capabilities. I invented confident learning and founded Cleanlab, a company that makes AI work reliably by curating the knowledge bases that power the AI systems. Before that, I created the CAMEO cheating detection system used to validate certificates in MITx and HarvardX online course teams. I am grateful to learned a ton working at places like Google AI, Oculus Research, Facebook AI Research, Amazon AI, Microsoft Research, NASA, MIT, and Harvard.

Growing up below the poverty line in rural Kentucky, I felt the glass ceiling of limited human and monetary resources. The ladder of opportunity often rises from prosperity rather than ability. My ladder was my education. Education led to exposure, summer programs, scholarships, and eventually opportunity. Everyone deserves access to quality educational resources – this underlies my motivation to pursue research that democratizes education and augments human learning and capabilities. This is why I spent my early years at MIT inventing the CAMEO cheating detection algorithm used to validate MITx and HarvardX certificates for open-access, free online courses, called MOOCs. And ultimately founded and continue to build companies that fill labor gaps needed for AI technology to empower people and the world we live in.

notable_achievements: Invented confident learning algorithms foundational to Cleanlab; Recipient of MIT Morris Levin Thesis Award; Recipient of National Science Foundation Fellowship; Recipient of Goldwater Scholarship; Worked at leading AI research groups including Google, Oculus, Amazon, Facebook, Microsoft, and NASA

name: Neel Master
title: Co-founder & CEO of Cedana
location: New York, New York, United States
about:
Hi, I'm Neel, co-founder and CEO of Cedana. 

For over a decade, I've experienced AI workload complexity explode—from simple ML models to GenAI distributed training, multi-modal, and agentic workflows. This complexity is now growing far faster than our ability to manually manage the underlying infrastructure.

I saw this firsthand during my computer vision and robotics research at MIT, and over several years building my Healthcare AI company, Engooden (acquired by SLQT). 

My co-founder, Niranjan, witnessed the same inevitable trend while building warehouse automation robotics at SixRiver (acquired by Shopify). 

We both knew a breaking point was coming where human-led DevOps could no longer keep up.

That's why we built Cedana. 

We're creating the autonomous infrastructure layer for the next era of AI, freeing human ingenuity to focus on discovery instead of fighting a losing battle with tools.

➡️ If you're an AI builder feeling this pain, I'd love to connect. https://tinyurl.com/54xpspp
speaking_engagements: Guest on Thinking Machines Podcast discussing GPUs and cloud computing with Cedana founder Neel Master
notable_achievements: Founded Neil Patel Digital, a leading digital marketing agency generating around $100 million annually; Built multiple startups with rapid growth, including seven startups reaching $1 million in first 12 months and three exceeding $10 million; Mentored over 3,500 other businesses

name: Jeff Rollason
title: Research collaborations with AI & Games Network at AI Factory research interests
about:
From my background as Systems Manager and Lecturing at London University, and long history in creating computer game engines, my goal has been to head-up the creation of a company that specialises in game AI. Result: AI Factory Ltd. With this came the need to develop a solid generic AI API and testbed architecture to allow easy 3rd party integration of game engines into their products. This took the name "Fireball" (for obscure historical reasons) and has now provided a successful and widely adopted cross-platform API for any game application. This necessary product was borne from my experience of observing the sometimes grievous difficulties experienced by other games companies attempting to take on 3rd party engines. 
After 11 years of incremental development, we are where we need to be, with our engines appearing in so many game applications, from PC, console, mobile and IFE. We have an estimated 200 million people using our game engines. The company has just 3 founder shareholder/employees, expanding any needed bandwidth by partnering other companies for specific projects.

Specialties: # 35 years in AI, having created some 40 game engines.
# Managerial, from running major courses in London University and also heading up AI Factory Ltd

speaking_engagements: Interview on start-up pitfalls and business advice; CEO commentary on airline entertainment technology
notable_achievements: Author of chess programs Treebeard, Merlin, and Rasputin; Co-created the game Sticky Blocks released in 2011; Contributed to AI and game programming research recognized at AIIDE conferences

name: Johannes Hagemann
title: co-founder / CTO @ Prime Intellect (we're hiring)
about:
I'm an SF based AI researcher and co-founder of Prime Intellect. Subjects I love to discuss to no end are decentralized AI, semi, energy abundance, definite techno-optimism, BCIs and many others - far too many for a currently normal lifespan, which is one of the reasons I'm also into longevity.

After reading the Scaling Hypothesis in 2020, I got extremely scaling-pilled and shifted my entire focus to LLMs. I joined Aleph Alpha over two years ago, helping build a novel, distributed training framework from scratch with state-of-the-art efficiency.
Following endlessly discussions on the latest AI research, traveling together to ICML, NeurIPS and more, Vincent Weisser and I decided at end of 2023 to go all in on Prime Intellect to build our vision of an open and decentralized future of AI.

At Prime Intellect we are building the infrastructure for decentralized AI development at scale. We aggregate global compute and enable researchers to collaboratively train state-of-the-art models through distributed training across clusters.

We have recently raised $15mm in funding led by Founders Fund, with participation from Karpathy, Tri Dao, Dylan Patel, Clem Delangue, Emad Mostaque and many others.
We are hiring for Full-Stack Engineers, Researchers and more, apply here: https://jobs.ashbyhq.com/PrimeIntellect

name: Finn Mallery
title: Founding sales @ Origami (YC F24) | Sharing insights from sales leaders who win @ Modern GTM
about:
Hey I'm Luke! I'd like my reputation to be: "talk to that guy and you'll leave energized, thinking about something new, good things will happen, and it'll generally cost you nothing.”

Currently, I'm part of Origami's exceptional founding team.

We build Research Agents who find prospects that fit nuanced filters and would take SDRs hours to sniff out manually.

Well at least initially...

Scaled that to $50k/mo in 2-3 months. No frontend. Just CSVs of incredible data.

Then, customers started using our Agents to make their CRM a live database.
Refreshing records, surfacing buying signals, tracking champions, etc.

Interesting...

Most recently, we learned our Agents could repair dysfunctional CRM structures.
Parent/child mapping, outdated account info, etc.

Pretty sick!

Now, we build AI Research Agents that work from your CRM to autonomously handle tasks like:

- Finding upsell opportunities through M&A
- Fixing incorrect or duplicate records
- Tracking your champions when they move
- Enriching missing contact info
- Updating outdated info on your accounts 
- Finding new data points for your outbound 
- Gathering data from PDFs, complex search bars, locators, scroll feeds, and unique databases

We’ve deployed hundreds of Research Agents to work like humans for the fastest-growing sales teams.

Some stats:
- We were YC's fastest growing startup in 2024.
- We've helped companies close over $20M in revenue.
- Our avg customer does 3.4x their previous meeting book rates.

If that's interesting, see if an agent can unlock your CRM here: www.origamiagents.com/get-started

--
I also love jamming on outbound, AI x GTM, and how this whole space is evolving.
That's why I started Modern GTM, an interview-newsletter with a few thousand readers.

Find more flavor about me @ lukeclancy.com (where I'm attempting to become the most curious man in America).

title: CEO & Co-Founder at Simular | Creating autonomous computers | Ex-Google DeepMind Research Scientist | 2x World Finalist Programmer | The future of digital experiences
about:
What if your computer could work independently, just like a human assistant?

After a decade in AI research at Google DeepMind, something still deeply puzzled me: we spend 2.5 hours daily just moving our computer mouse. That's 30% of our work time on mechanical tasks.

This realization led me to build Simular AI. We're creating AI agents that use computers like humans do - clicking, typing, and navigating interfaces - so you can focus on what truly matters.

My journey spans:

- Research: 39 papers in top AI venues (NeurIPS, ICML, CVPR, ICLR)
- Engineering: Scaled AI systems at Google (Ads, Maps, YouTube)
- Leadership: Built & led teams in autonomous driving
- Competition: 2x World Finalist in ACM/ICPC

Now, I'm on a mission to democratize AI assistance. Because the future of work isn't about replacing humans - it's about augmenting them.

Want to see the future of human-computer interaction?
→ Visit simular.ai
→ Follow my insights on X @angli_ai

name: Chris Walti
title: Co-Founder / CEO of Mytra
about:
I'm applying two decades of software and hardware engineering experience to the massive challenge of modernizing automation for supply chain and manufacturing industries. The strain on supply chains and manufacturing systems require immediate and disruptive solutions. PLCs are rigid by design and today's "industrial" products are 4x the cost with .25x the capability vs. standard enterprise tools. Most organizations don't have legions of control engineers to roll out needed systems or take on the tech debt. Mytra provides a platform to simply and efficiently solve the most common task in industry - moving and storing material throughout the facility. These non value add tasks employ between 25-75% of the labor for any industrial operation. Mytra develops a novel racking structure providing a 3D grid traversable along all 3 axes, robots to move material within the system, and the software to easily design, operate, and continuously optimize without the need for automation engineers.

Previous to Mytra I created and led Tesla's Mobile Robotics team. We design, develop, build, and deploy robots across Tesla's manufacturing portfolio. The team includes mechanical, electrical, software, controls, perception, manufacturing, and operations experts. We create wheeled mobile robots that serve our factories, and also develop the humanoid Tesla Bot (Optimus).

My professional experiences involve leading engineering teams to design and launch new products, both as an entrepreneur and an "intrapreneur" (within existing companies). They combine hardware and software. The technical challenges/risk and level of responsibility have increased with each role.

name: Satya Nitta

about:
I have an abiding interest in all aspects of computing, especially AI and silicon technology. Other interests span: Cosmology, life sciences including astrobiology, nanoscale phenomena and conservation of species and habitats.

I'm an entrepreneur, technologist and inventor. My formal background is in the physics of nanoscale phenomena which I worked on during my Ph.D. My career since then has been split into two parts. For the 2nd part of my career, I have been working in AI (conversational systems and NLP) and this has spanned the better part of the last 15 years. name: George Strompolos
title: Co-Founder & CEO at Promise
about:
George Strompolos is the Co-Founder and CEO at Promise, an entertainment studio powered by Generative AI creators and storytellers. 

George is renowned for his pioneering contributions to the creator economy. 

In 2007, George co-created the YouTube Partner Program, enabling millions of video creators worldwide to earn money from their work. Today this program is the largest creator monetization product in the world.

In 2011, George founded Fullscreen, a groundbreaking media/tech company that helped creators build audiences on social media and advance their creative careers. Under his leadership, Fullscreen became a major force in the creator economy and was ultimately acquired by AT&T / WarnerMedia in 2018 for $850M.

George is an inventor on multiple patents including Google’s patent for the monetization of user-generated content and Fullscreen’s patent for technology to match creators with brand sponsors.

George’s story has been featured in numerous books documenting the rise of social media and the creator economy, including "Extremely Online: The Untold Story of Fame, Influence, and Power on the Internet", and "Like, Comment, Subscribe: Inside YouTube's Chaotic Rise to World Domination".

George is an active angel investor and startup advisor. His portfolio includes companies such as Flexport, Liquid Death, Mr. Beast’s Feastables, Moonpay, Oxide Computer, Giggster, RedCircle, CreatorNow, CashDrop and Angel City FC.

A passionate philanthropist, George oversees the Strompolos Family Foundation with his wife Kristin. Together they support non-profits across the arts, education, community development, and children’s needs. George currently serves on the board of KCRW in Los Angeles.

George is a proud father of young two children, Penelope and Dean. He loves the outdoors, surfing, snowboarding, traveling, cooking, playing guitar and spending time with his family.

Dave Clark is an award-winning filmmaker at the forefront of integrating Generative AI into film, TV, and advertising. He is currently the Co-Founder and Chief Creative Officer at Promise. Recognized as a leading voice for his ability to seamlessly blend nuanced storytelling with cutting-edge technology, he has become one of the most sought-after artists, with top filmmakers and storytellers worldwide turning to him for guidance on this transformative technology.

Clark recently amassed millions of views for his groundbreaking AI directing work, including his short film “Battalion,” which focused on the only Black unit to arrive on Omaha Beach in Normandy during World War 2. It quickly captured the attention of Hollywood, with many top directors reaching out to learn more about the technology behind it. Dave also garnered widespread acclaim when he released the world’s first hybrid narrative genre short, “Another,” combining live-action and GenAI. Over his career, Dave has also been a successful brand marketer and commercial director –  creating films, immersive engagements, and brand spots for companies like Coca-Cola, Snapchat, Hewlett Packard, Warner Bros., and Intel. 

Dave has spoken about the future of filmmaking at prestigious events around the globe (including the Berlinale, MIT, Indiewire, Picture This Conference, and the Cannes Film Festival).  He resides in Southern California with his wife and children.

name: Alfred Wahlforss
title: AI-led customer interviews for UX and insights teams | CEO & Co-Founder @ Listen Labs
about:
At Harvard, my co-founder Florian and I built an AI avatar app that exploded overnight: Front page of reddit, 20k downloads per day - but $1,000/h in GPU costs on our personal credit cards. 

In order not to go broke, we had to get users to stay on the platform long enough. And for that we had to talk to them. 

Problem was: We couldn’t talk to 1,000s of users 1on1. 

So we built an AI to do it for us. 

One that listens to every customer and deeply understands what they care about.

It worked so well that we thought: 

What if every company could do this?

- Talk to hundreds of customers simultaneously
- Listen to & understand their preferences
- Turn them into actionable insights

This is exactly what Listen Labs does today.

Whether you're testing products or exploring new markets, Listen is a skilled researcher that works 24/7, delivering insights in hours instead of weeks.

Leading companies like Microsoft, Canva, Chubbies, and others use our insights to make more customer-driven decisions.

We’ve also raised $27M from Sequoia to help as many companies as possible understand their customers better, faster.

If you’d like to know more, reach out to: alfred@listenlabs.ai

Search under "Active Inference", "Free Energy Principle", "Dr. Karl Friston"

"Collective Intelligence" Summary

name: Christoph Lassner
title: 3D and 4D perception, rendering and generation.
about:
I am deeply curious about how we can build virtual representations for the real world that can be optimized and rendered efficiently to faithfully match our perception (visual and beyond; see for example my projects on Neural Assets, VEO, Neural 3D Video, NR-NeRF - links on my website). A lot of my work focuses on perception and rendering systems for humans, see for example TAVA, HVH, ARCH, NBF, UP. I created the human pose estimation system for Amazon Halo, which is part of a system to create a 3D model of your body using your smartphone. My team’s work at Meta on reconstructing and rendering radiance fields interactively was featured at Meta Connect 2022 and on CNET (co-presented with Zhao Dong et al.’s work on inverse rendering).

At the same time, I am very interested in the engineering challenges such systems create and was awarded an Honorable Mention at the ACM Multimedia Open-Source Software Competition 2016 for my work on decision forests. In 2021, I wrote the Pulsar renderer (now the sphere-based rendering backend for PyTorch3D) and would love to find better ways to use low-level autodifferentiation on GPUs.

If you would like to work together on challenges at the intersection of machine learning, computer graphics and computer vision (from modeling to engineering), please reach out!
speaking_engagements: VASC Seminar on Towards Interactive Radiance Fields, January 2023
notable_achievements: Co-founder of World Labs, a spatial intelligence AI company building Large World Models (LWMs); Lead Research Scientist at Epic Games; Research Scientist Manager at Meta contributing to Pulsar differentiable renderer for PyTorch3D and real-time rendering system; Applied Scientist at Amazon designing human pose estimation for Amazon Halo app
reasoning: Christoph Lassner demonstrates strong technical expertise and research credentials with a PhD in Computer Science and significant technical contributions in computer vision and AI. His work history shows senior technical achievements including creating core technology for Amazon Halo and notable contributions at Meta. While he's now a co-founder, his profile suggests he's primarily a technical expert moving into entrepreneurship rather than a seasoned founder.
